         I don't really see what this has to do with being old-school pet control necro or not though. From my point of view, this has to do with them not having the same rules applied to all pets without telling people about it.</P><P>Consider this: you're told that your pet won't break mez. For all of us old-schoolers (sheesh, that's the entire necro community since the change is like a month old) all this means is we don't have to hit the /pet calm down button to prevent it from breaking mez (for those of us who don't have /pet hold yet).</P><P>Yet, then comes along this thing where charmed pets seem to ignore these rules and go breaking mez all over the place. Now, in a place like HS, that's usually no biggie. But in a slightly tougher location, say Chardok, it could mean that your chanter gets a random beating, won't be terribly happy about it and starts pointing fingers at the necro who doesn't know how to control his pet. A pet which VI says doesn't need controlling.</P><P>At the end of the day, it probably won't make much of a difference. Everyone who charms on a constant basis will remember it. But, groups will probably get stung by it at least once. And it could happen in a much worse situation than HS and wouldn't be a very pleasant surprise.</P><P>Which is why I'm asking whether it's a known effect or a bug (either systemwide or only in HS). If it's not something that's known, then I've at least done my part in communicating it to others. I can also then follow up on it on the support board or something. If it's something that's already well known, then I won't bother doing anything about it.</P><P>Oh and btw, found another example of charmed pets behaving according to old pet rules: in HS (again), charmed a skele that was standing next to 2 bile golems. Golems proceeded to attack pet immediately, meaning that the pet wasn't non-aggro to mobs.</P><P>Tenaiya Soulscorcher<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="righ